HEADWORD: Necromancy
<hw>Nec"ro*man`cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nigromaunce</ets>, <ets>nigromancie</ets>, OF.
<ets>nigromance</ets>, F. <ets>n⟦eacute⟧cromance</ets>,
<ets>n⟦eacute⟧cromancie</ets>, from L. <ets>necromantia</ets>, Gr. <?/;
<grk>nekro`s</grk> a dead body (akin to L. <ets>necare</ets> to kill,
Skr. <ets>na⟦cced⟧</ets> to perish, vanish) + <?/ divination, fr. <?/
diviner, seer, akin to E. <ets>mania</ets>. See <er>Mania</er>, and cf.
<er>Internecine</er>, <er>Noxious</er>. The old spelling is due to
confusion with L. <ets>niger</ets> black. Hence the name <ets>black
art</ets>.]</ety> <def>The art of revealing future events by means of a
pretended communication with the dead; the black art; hence, magic in
general; conjuration; enchantment. See <er>Black art</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This palace standeth in the air,⟦br⟧
